<div id="review_559588296" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/559588296" />
    <a title="Morgan Blackledge" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3897817-morgan-blackledge"><img alt="Morgan Blackledge" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1281826346p2/3897817.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/559588296?book_show_action=true">Mar 12, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Morgan Blackledge" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Morgan Blackledge" href="/user/show/3897817-morgan-blackledge">Morgan Blackledge</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer559588296" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12346386822345861079">I hope everyone who is curious about processed food reads this book and shares it with their friends and family. This book describes the way the food industry, consumers, and the American economy came to rely so heavily on salt, sugar and fat. It&apos;s not as much a cabal or a conspiracy on the part of government and corporations, as it is a matter of very human, systemic factors that keep American food producers making and aggressively marketing &quot;food&quot; that is essentially engineered to addict. And </span>
  <span id="freeText12346386822345861079" style="display:none">I hope everyone who is curious about processed food reads this book and shares it with their friends and family. This book describes the way the food industry, consumers, and the American economy came to rely so heavily on salt, sugar and fat. It's not as much a cabal or a conspiracy on the part of government and corporations, as it is a matter of very human, systemic factors that keep American food producers making and aggressively marketing "food" that is essentially engineered to addict. And when I say addict, I mean it quite literally, not euphemistically (see The Pleasure Trap, by Doug Lisle). Engineered, calorie dense pleasure foods addict users (heavy user is an industry term for people who buy and eat lots of junk food and soda) via the same brain mechanisms as other addictive drugs, and have similar biological, psychological and social costs. There is hope, there is a way out. It entails educating our selves, getting needed support, and taking action to change our habits. This book should be a nice addition to anyone's education on this urgent and important public, community, family and individual health issue.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12346386822345861079" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


